lhave, perhaps incautiously, put the rule as to the initial qni, some· what too generally. lt often happens that the ordinary and strictly rela- tive clause is taken out of its natural position and put before that to which it belongs, either as an explanatory or objective clause, and thus qai will stand at the beginning of a period, where it is not referred to any subject immediately preceding it in the former period. Thus, qai recte vivendi ,prorogat horam rusticus expectat, Hor. Ep. i. 2, 41: qni capit oct metuit jurat illum, ibid. 51: qni nort moderabitur irre, infectum nolet esse, ibid. 59, where the qni in each case occurs after a full point.
